textDisplay:
My Pizza eggs recipe I have been doing for the past decade is almost exactly like yours. The only difference I use 3 eggs and when the pizza is cooked I throw the pizza into the eggs and mix and then dump in the pan. It gives it a more even consistency and bigger bites of egg. And when I plate it I sprinkle a layer of parm on the top.


Also, sometimes I go crazy and make tortillas and have a Pizza Egg Taco (actually not bad with a lil salsa or your favorite hot sauce)
textOriginal:
My Pizza eggs recipe I have been doing for the past decade is almost exactly like yours. The only difference I use 3 eggs and when the pizza is cooked I throw the pizza into the eggs and mix and then dump in the pan. It gives it a more even consistency and bigger bites of egg. And when I plate it I sprinkle a layer of parm on the top.


Also, sometimes I go crazy and make tortillas and have a Pizza Egg Taco (actually not bad with a lil salsa or your favorite hot sauce)

textDisplay: First off, great video ! But being a former chef, I do a lot of research into food. And that Japanese mayo is crap, it includes MSG , which is a "flavor enhancer "that many people get sick from and have asthma attacks. It basically opens the flavor pores in your tongue so things taste different. And usually found in Asian foods, because it's a cheap way of making foods taste better. I would change to Dukes mayo, it's the same thing without the MSG.

textDisplay:
1. The sauce is similar to big mac sauce as its a not so refined version of it. Add pepper, salt, sugar and little pieces of onion to it then finish it off with sour cream to get the big mac sauce, much more superb and refined.
2. For the meat forming and grilling process, this is wrong on so many levels, dont add oil to it... form it before you put it on the grill, salt it only from one side and put that side top first, the burger will magically not grow like a vulcano trust me, also do not form in on a grill... you can see how it all sticks to the little shovel(?)
3. Before you grill your meat grill your buns on the inside side without any butters, oils or anything like that, after that clean the grill if you have a flat one like this from the little pieces of bun or they will burn and stick to other food.
4. Nice trick with the onions but rest of this recipe is a disaster.
textOriginal:
1. The sauce is similar to big mac sauce as its a not so refined version of it. Add pepper, salt, sugar and little pieces of onion to it then finish it off with sour cream to get the big mac sauce, much more superb and refined.
2. For the meat forming and grilling process, this is wrong on so many levels, dont add oil to it... form it before you put it on the grill, salt it only from one side and put that side top first, the burger will magically not grow like a vulcano trust me, also do not form in on a grill... you can see how it all sticks to the little shovel(?) 
3. Before you grill your meat grill your buns on the inside side without any butters, oils or anything like that, after that clean the grill if you have a flat one like this from the little pieces of bun or they will burn and stick to other food.
4. Nice trick with the onions but rest of this recipe is a disaster.

textDisplay:
For UK watchers of this Channel! On Sam's recommendation I ordered Kewpie Mayonnaise from Amazon. £3.75 so quite expensive for Mayo.

Anyway, the way Sam goes on about it I thought I have to try it, I'm expecting something very different to regular Mayo... And it is!!

But, here in the UK we have something that's much cheaper and tastes near identical. Developed by Heinz UK, for the UK market in 1919...

Salad Cream. Yup! Kewpie tastes like Heinz Salad Cream.

Ok, I'm sure Kewpie is better quality ingredients, etc etc, but at least you should know what kind of flavour profile this Mayo has. If you don't like Salad Cream, you won't like this.
textOriginal:
For UK watchers of this Channel! On Sam's recommendation I ordered Kewpie Mayonnaise from Amazon. £3.75 so quite expensive for Mayo. 

Anyway, the way Sam goes on about it I thought I have to try it, I'm expecting something very different to regular Mayo... And it is!! 

But, here in the UK we have something that's much cheaper and tastes near identical. Developed by Heinz UK, for the UK market in 1919...

Salad Cream. Yup! Kewpie tastes like Heinz Salad Cream. 

Ok, I'm sure Kewpie is better quality ingredients, etc etc, but at least you should know what kind of flavour profile this Mayo has. If you don't like Salad Cream, you won't like this.

textDisplay:
I’m truly sorry Sam,

I love your recipes, but I simply HAD to express what a turn off it is when you talk, burn yourself, and sputter about with your mouth during your shows! I don’t mean to be picky, it’s just something I have a hard time listening to and seeing.

I realize you’re eager to sample your delicious recipes, but maybe you can become aware of some folks’ feelings about this topic. Thank you for your wonderful show, I’ll do my best to be strong and continue watching for a bit, I really hope this will change. You’re great, keep up the wonderful work you do.
Regards,
Susan M. Gowen

textDisplay:
The term “carne asada” means grilled meat. You grilled it, but left it mooing. Not typical of Mexican carne asada. It’s usually well done.

Another delicious and tasty cut is lomo con diezmillo. Tons of flavor. For a simple marinade, use “Chef Mérito” red seasoning (found in most Latino/Mexican stores in CA etc.) and squeeze some oranges.

Let rest for 30 minutes and fire up the coles. It’s pretty good. Your recipe was different, but it’s probably on the sweet end. Oh! And don’t forget to whip up a great salsa and guacamole!!
textOriginal:
The term “carne asada” means grilled meat. You grilled it, but left it mooing. Not typical of Mexican carne asada. It’s usually well done.

Another delicious and tasty cut is lomo con diezmillo. Tons of flavor. For a simple marinade, use “Chef Mérito” red seasoning (found in most Latino/Mexican stores in CA etc.) and squeeze some oranges. 

Let rest for 30 minutes and fire up the coles. It’s pretty good. Your recipe was different, but it’s probably on the sweet end. Oh! And don’t forget to whip up a great salsa and guacamole!!

textDisplay: My Father was not a racist, but he made doughnuts for Krispy Kreme Doughnut Factory for at least 20 years.  When I was in high school, I renamed them Drippy Dreme Donut Factory and he thought that was hilarious.  Every Christmas, we had ham and my Father had to have Jewish rye bread with Caraway seeds for the sandwiches he would take to work.  But one day, my Father's world somehow collided with bagels.  How dare a food that looked like a donut not be sweet!!!  He dogged bagels for the rest of his life and I, having learned of everything bagels with vegetable cream cheese and cinnamon/ raisin bagels with cream cheese, apple jelly, toasted walnuts with crumbled bacon on top, had to eat them on the sly.  lol
textOriginal: My Father was not a racist, but he made doughnuts for Krispy Kreme Doughnut Factory for at least 20 years.  When I was in high school, I renamed them Drippy Dreme Donut Factory and he thought that was hilarious.  Every Christmas, we had ham and my Father had to have Jewish rye bread with Caraway seeds for the sandwiches he would take to work.  But one day, my Father's world somehow collided with bagels.  How dare a food that looked like a donut not be sweet!!!  He dogged bagels for the rest of his life and I, having learned of everything bagels with vegetable cream cheese and cinnamon/ raisin bagels with cream cheese, apple jelly, toasted walnuts with crumbled bacon on top, had to eat them on the sly.  lol
